.TH "ELEMENT.INSERTADJACENTHTML" "3JS" "August 11, 2025" "JavaScript" "JavaScript Reference Manual"
.SH NAME
Element.insertAdjacentHTML \- Element: insertAdjacentHTML() method
.SH SYNOPSIS
.RS
.PP
\f[B]Warning:\f[R] This method parses its input as HTML or XML, writing
the result into the DOM.
APIs like this are known as injection sinks, and are potentially a
vector for cross\-site\-scripting (XSS) attacks, if the input originally
came from an attacker.
.PP
You can reduce the risk by assigning \f[CR]TrustedHTML\f[R] objects
instead of strings, and enforcing trusted types using the
\f[CR]require\-trusted\-types\-for\f[R] CSP directive.
This ensures that the input is passed through a transformation function,
which has the chance to sanitize the input to remove potentially
dangerous markup, such as \f[CR]<script>\f[R] elements and event handler
attributes.
.RE
.PP
The \f[B]\f[CB]insertAdjacentHTML()\f[B]\f[R] method of the
\f[CR]Element\f[R] interface parses the specified input as HTML or XML
and inserts the resulting nodes into the DOM tree at a specified
position.
.SH SYNTAX
.IP
.EX
insertAdjacentHTML(position, input)
.EE
.SS Parameters
.TP
\f[B]position\f[R]
A string representing the position relative to the element.
Must be one of the following strings:
.RS
.TP
\f[B]\(dqbeforebegin\(dq\f[R]
Before the element.
Only valid if the element is in the DOM tree and has a parent element.
.TP
\f[B]\(dqafterbegin\(dq\f[R]
Just inside the element, before its first child.
.TP
\f[B]\(dqbeforeend\(dq\f[R]
Just inside the element, after its last child.
.TP
\f[B]\(dqafterend\(dq\f[R]
After the element.
Only valid if the element is in the DOM tree and has a parent element.
.RE
.TP
\f[B]input\f[R]
A \f[CR]TrustedHTML\f[R] instance or string defining the HTML or XML to
be parsed.
.SS Return value
None (\f[CR]undefined\f[R]).
.SS Exceptions
This method may raise a \f[CR]DOMException\f[R] of one of the following
types:
.TP
\f[B]NoModificationAllowedError\f[R] \f[B]DOMException\f[R]
Thrown if \f[CR]position\f[R] is \f[CR]\(dqbeforebegin\(dq\f[R] or
\f[CR]\(dqafterend\(dq\f[R] and the element either does not have a
parent or its parent is the \f[CR]Document\f[R] object.
.TP
\f[B]SyntaxError\f[R] \f[B]DOMException\f[R]
Thrown if:
.RS
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]position\f[R] is not one of the four listed values.
.IP \(bu 2
The input is XML that is not well\-formed.
.RE
.TP
\f[B]TypeError\f[R]
Thrown if the property is set to a string when Trusted Types are
enforced by a CSP and no default policy is defined.
.SH DESCRIPTION
The \f[CR]insertAdjacentHTML()\f[R] method does not reparse the element
it is being used on, and thus it does not corrupt the existing elements
inside that element.
This avoids the extra step of serialization, making it much faster than
direct \f[CR]innerHTML\f[R] manipulation.
.PP
Where \f[CR]<p>\f[R] is the element, we can visualize the possible
positions for the inserted content \(lqfoo\(rq as follows:
.IP
.EX
\f[I]<!\-\- beforebegin \-\->\f[R]
<\f[B]p\f[R]>
  \f[I]<!\-\- afterbegin \-\->\f[R]
  foo
  \f[I]<!\-\- beforeend \-\->\f[R]
</\f[B]p\f[R]>
\f[I]<!\-\- afterend \-\->\f[R]
.EE
.PP
The method does not include any special handling for
\f[CR]<template>\f[R] elements.
In most cases developers should use \f[CR]insertAdjacentHTML()\f[R] on
the template\(cqs \f[CR]content\f[R] property instead of directly
manipulating the child nodes of a template element.
.SS Security considerations
The method does not perform any sanitization to remove XSS\-unsafe
elements such as \f[CR]<script>\f[R], or event handler content
attributes.
.PP
When inserting HTML into a page using \f[CR]insertAdjacentHTML()\f[R],
you should pass \f[CR]TrustedHTML\f[R] objects instead of strings, and
enforce trusted types using the \f[CR]require\-trusted\-types\-for\f[R]
CSP directive.
This ensures that the input is passed through a transformation function,
which has the chance to sanitize the input to remove potentially
dangerous markup before it is injected.
.PP
The \f[CR]Element.insertAdjacentText()\f[R] method or
\f[CR]Node.textContent\f[R] should be used when you know that the user
provided content should be plain text.
This inserts the input as raw text instead of parsing it as HTML.
.SH EXAMPLES
.SS Inserting HTML
This example demonstrates the four insertion positions.
All inserted text is bold, while text inserted inside the element is
further styled as red monotype (code).
.SS HTML
.IP
.EX
<\f[B]select\f[R] id=\(dqposition\(dq>
  <\f[B]option\f[R]>beforebegin</\f[B]option\f[R]>
  <\f[B]option\f[R]>afterbegin</\f[B]option\f[R]>
  <\f[B]option\f[R]>beforeend</\f[B]option\f[R]>
  <\f[B]option\f[R]>afterend</\f[B]option\f[R]>
</\f[B]select\f[R]>

<\f[B]button\f[R] id=\(dqinsert\(dq>Insert HTML</\f[B]button\f[R]>
<\f[B]button\f[R] id=\(dqreset\(dq>Reset</\f[B]button\f[R]>

<\f[B]p\f[R]>
  Some text, with a <\f[B]code\f[R] id=\(dqsubject\(dq>code\-formatted element</\f[B]code\f[R]> inside it.
</\f[B]p\f[R]>
.EE
.SS CSS
.IP
.EX
code {
  \f[B]color\f[R]: red;
}
.EE
.SS JavaScript
Trusted types are not yet supported on all browsers, so first we define
the trusted types tinyfill.
This acts as a transparent replacement for the trusted types JavaScript
API:
.IP
.EX
\f[B]if\f[R] (\f[B]typeof\f[R] trustedTypes === \(dqundefined\(dq)
  trustedTypes = { createPolicy: (n, rules) \f[B]=>\f[R] rules };
.EE
.PP
Next we define a policy named \f[CR]some\-content\-policy\f[R] to create
\f[CR]TrustedHTML\f[R] objects from the input (we should also enforce
the \f[CR]some\-content\-policy\f[R] using CSP).
The code implements no\-op policy in order to allow this example to work
without a third\-party dependency.
Your own application code should use a third party library such as the
\(lqDOMPurify\(rq library to return sanitized content from the untrusted
input.
.IP
.EX
\f[B]const\f[R] policy = trustedTypes.createPolicy(\(dqsome\-content\-policy\(dq, {
  createHTML(input) {
    \f[B]return\f[R] input; \f[I]// Do not do this in your own code!\f[R]
    \f[I]// Instead do something like:\f[R]
    \f[I]// return DOMPurify.sanitize(input);\f[R]
  },
});

\f[B]const\f[R] unsafeText = \(dq<strong>inserted text</strong>\(dq;
\f[B]const\f[R] trustedHTML = policy.createHTML(unsafeText);
.EE
.PP
The remaining code inserts the trusted HTML at the selected position
relative to the element with id \f[CR]subject\f[R].
.IP
.EX
\f[B]const\f[R] insert = document.querySelector(\(dq#insert\(dq);
insert.addEventListener(\(dqclick\(dq, () \f[B]=>\f[R] {
  \f[B]const\f[R] subject = document.querySelector(\(dq#subject\(dq);
  \f[B]const\f[R] positionSelect = document.querySelector(\(dq#position\(dq);
  subject.insertAdjacentHTML(positionSelect.value, trustedHTML);
});

\f[B]const\f[R] reset = document.querySelector(\(dq#reset\(dq);
reset.addEventListener(\(dqclick\(dq, () \f[B]=>\f[R] {
  document.location.reload();
});
.EE
.SS Result
